# about
I am currently working with professors <a>Anirudh Sivaraman,https://anirudhsk.github.io/</a> and <a>Joseph Tassarotti,https://cs.nyu.edu/~jt4767/</a>.
During undergrad, I was supervised by <a>Peter Dinda,http://www.pdinda.org/</a> and worked with <a>Mike Wilkins,https://mjwilkins.org/</a> and <a>Peizhi Liu,https://peizhiliu.com/</a>.
My research primarily lies within HPC; after all, if computer science is interesting, then <em>big computer</em> science must certainly be more interesting.
I can be contacted at s.rhee@nyu.edu or by pure chance in public.

# on research
(Almost) nobody <em>dislikes</em> performance, but actually doing performance engineering is a complete pain, especially as hardware stacks get more complex. This is not news. But b/c of that, the most exciting space in HPC research isn't just about exposing performance, but also about making said performance tractable to actually extract.
Right now, I'm most curious about how to better leverage programmable networks in distributed workloads and how to improve tooling around programmable networks, and at the moment, my active research is exploring how formal verification might guide automated code generation in these contexts.

